<li id="cite_note-19"><b><a href="#cite_ref-19" title="">^</a></b> The "hyndez" (hinds) first described in the poem are probably from <a href="/wiki/Red_deer" title="Red deer" class="mw-redirect">red deer</a>, a species with large antlers like the <a href="/wiki/Elk" title="Elk">American elk</a>, while the subsequent "dos and of oþer dere" (does and other deer) likely refer to the smaller <a href="/wiki/Fallow_deer" title="Fallow deer" class="mw-redirect">fallow deer</a>. (Ong, Walter J. "The Green Knight's Harts and Bucks". <i>Modern Language Notes</i>. (December 1950) 65.8 pp.&#160;536–539.)</li>
